---
/**
 * Keep inline tags on one line with outer spaces (Astro whitespace).
 * Never break before <em>/<strong>/<a> after a word.
 */
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Dennett: The Narrative Self and Multiple Drafts of Consciousness | Foundations | Identity Engineering">
	<main class="min-h-screen">
		<section class="border-b border-white/10 px-6 pt-28 pb-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
				<a href="/foundations" class="mb-6 inline-block text-sm text-white/40 transition hover:text-white/70">
					← Foundations
				</a>
				<div class="text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Foundations · Dennett</div>
				<h1 class="mt-3 text-5xl font-bold tracking-tighter leading-[0.95] text-white md:text-6xl">
					The Narrative Self and Multiple Drafts of Consciousness
				</h1>
				<p class="mt-6 max-w-2xl text-xl font-light leading-relaxed text-white/50">
					The idea that there is no single, unified Cartesian theater in the mind. Consciousness and the self emerge as a center of narrative gravity constructed from multiple parallel processes.
				</p>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-12 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div class="rounded-2xl border border-white/10 bg-white/[0.03] p-5 text-base leading-relaxed text-white/60">
					<strong class="text-white/80">Reading protocol on this page:</strong>
					First Dennett in his own terms. Then inspirations for Identity Engineering.
					Then additions from Identity Engineering perspective.
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">1 · The Multiple Drafts Model</div>
					<p>
						In *Consciousness Explained* (1991) Daniel Dennett argues against the traditional "Cartesian theater" model of consciousness — the idea that there is a central place in the brain where everything comes together and is presented to a single conscious self.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Instead, he proposes the **Multiple Drafts Model**: at any moment there are multiple parallel processes in the brain generating different versions ("drafts") of what is happening. Consciousness is not a single finished product but the ongoing editing and competition among these drafts. There is no final "broadcast" to a central observer.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">2 · The Narrative Self and the Center of Narrative Gravity</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-white/10 bg-black/20 p-4 text-sm text-white/60">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Core idea (Dennett):</strong> The self is not a substantial thing or inner witness. It is a **center of narrative gravity** — a useful fiction we construct by telling stories about ourselves. Just as the center of gravity of a physical object is a useful abstraction, the self is a useful abstraction that emerges from our narrative practices.
					</div>
					<p>
						We constantly edit and revise our personal narratives. These narratives create a sense of continuity and identity even though there is no single, unified "I" behind them. The self is the ongoing product of this narrative activity rather than its author in a traditional sense.
					</p>
					<p class="mt-4">
						Dennett is a reductionist: once we understand all the physical and functional processes, there is no further fact of a "real" self beyond the narrative constructions we maintain.
					</p>
				</div>

				<div>
					<div class="mb-3 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">3 · Relevance for Identity Engineering</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-400/20 bg-cyan-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Inspiration from Dennett:</strong> the self is a constructed, narrative, and distributed phenomenon rather than a fixed inner substance. This makes conscious intervention in our narratives a powerful way to reshape identity.
					</div>
					<div class="mb-4 rounded-xl border border-violet-400/20 bg-violet-400/[0.04] p-4 text-sm text-white/65">
						<strong class="text-white/80">IE additions:</strong> treating the ongoing editing of personal narratives as a primary mechanism for curving and maintaining the Identity Stem; using Questions as Probes to examine and revise the "drafts" we live by; and understanding that identity coherence is an active, distributed achievement rather than the discovery of a pre-existing core.
					</div>
					<ul class="space-y-4">
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Narrative as Stem maintenance:</strong> Dennett shows that much of what feels like a stable self is the result of constant narrative editing. Conscious work on the stories we tell ourselves is direct work on the coherence and direction of the Identity Stem.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Multiple drafts as distributed geometry:</strong> Identity is not a single fixed structure but the product of multiple parallel processes. This supports the idea that the Stem can be influenced at many points through targeted probes and narrative interventions.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Center of narrative gravity as useful abstraction:</strong> The self is a useful fiction we maintain. Identity Engineering can be understood as the deliberate improvement of this useful fiction — making the narrative center stronger, more coherent, and better oriented toward open futures.
						</li>
						<li>
							<strong class="text-white/80">Bridge between Parfit and Ricœur:</strong> Dennett connects Parfit’s reductionist view (there is no deep self) with Ricœur’s narrative approach by showing how we nevertheless construct a livable and functional self through storytelling.
						</li>
					</ul>
					<p class="mt-6">
						<strong class="text-white/80">Differentiation:</strong> Dennett offers a functionalist and reductionist account of the narrative self that sits between Parfit’s strict reductionism and Ricœur’s more hermeneutic emphasis on meaning. He shows that even if the self is "just" a center of narrative gravity, this construction is enormously powerful and can be consciously improved. This strengthens the justification for deliberate narrative and probing work on identity geometry.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 bg-white/[0.015] px-6 py-16">
			<div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl space-y-8 text-lg leading-relaxed text-white/55">
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Sources</div>
					<ul class="space-y-2 text-base text-white/50">
						<li>
							Primary: Daniel C. Dennett, <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Consciousness Explained</em> (1991), <em class="text-white/75 not-italic">Self as a Center of Narrative Gravity</em> (1992).
						</li>
						<li>
							Overview: <a href="https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/dennett/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-white/70 underline decoration-white/25 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white hover:decoration-white/50">Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy: Dennett</a>.
						</li>
					</ul>
				</div>
				<div>
					<div class="mb-2 text-sm uppercase tracking-[4px] text-white/40">Related</div>
					<p>
						Dennett is a key bridge between analytic philosophy of mind and narrative approaches to the self. He complements Parfit’s reductionism and Ricœur’s hermeneutics by showing how a functional, distributed view of consciousness supports the idea of the self as an actively constructed and revisable narrative center. This anchor strengthens the case for conscious narrative work as a primary tool of identity design.
					</p>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<section class="border-t border-white/10 px-6 py-14">
			<div class="mx-auto flex max-w-3xl flex-col gap-4 text-sm sm:flex-row sm:items-center sm:justify-between">
				<a href="/foundations" class="text-white/50 transition hover:text-white/80">← All foundations</a>
				<div class="flex flex-wrap gap-x-6 gap-y-2">
					<a href="/ontology" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Ontology</a>
					<a href="/blog" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Blog</a>
					<a href="/framework" class="text-white/50 underline decoration-white/20 underline-offset-4 transition hover:text-white/80 hover:decoration-white/40">Framework</a>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
	</main>
</Layout>
